metadata.name: Clerestory #120
metadata.description:
Windows welcome daylight, admit fresh air, and offer a view into the outside world. They rarely shatter, always confess the passage of time, and sometimes allow others a chance to look in.

What would the space you're in feel like if it had no windows?

'Clerestory' is an abstract exploration of stained glass windows, drafting shattered sketches for ten potential locations from various perspectives and moments in time. 

Made with WebGL, p5.js, and <3 | CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Winesburg, Ohio #27
metadata.description: â€œWinesburg, Ohioâ€ is an act of uncanny place-making. The collection borrows its name from a 1919 short-story cycle by Sherwood Anderson, which explores a peculiar cast of characters living within a fictionalized, midwestern town. Like Andersonâ€™s text, the â€œWinesburg, Ohioâ€ algorithm constructs a world through recurring portrayals of specific structures and landmarks. Its scenes are populated by a variety of familiar elements taken from my larger body of work, including water towers, houses, and churches. Meanwhile, a series of scripted gestures insert abstract compositional elements into the outputs, counteracting their pictorial legibility. The strange landscapes that result are composite ideograms, comprised of multiple spatial possibilities that co-exist in varying states of contradiction.

metadata.name: Rapport #109
metadata.description:
The concept of nexus is a powerful one. It speaks to the idea that everything is related and that each part is necessary to create the whole. Rapport is about the relationship these parts have, harmonious or discordant, to convey a sense of unity and purpose. You are invited to explore the details and interactions of each object in its surroundings, recognizing the immense value they all have in building greater things.

A few shortcuts are available in live mode:
1 : Toggle the view (fit screen / original size)
T : Toggle paper texture
S : Save current view
H : Re-render in high resolution

The piece might require high processing power depending on its features. A good desktop or laptop running chrome is recommended.

Created with p5.js and GLSL
dmarchi, 2023.

metadata.name: MetaSignal: Lexicon #47
metadata.description:
The project is a reinterpretation of my previous "MetaSignal", with a different key.

Two one-dimensional 3-states cellular automata intersect to form a grid with a total of nine states.
A two-dimensional cellular automata extracts details from the grid.

This complex configuration enhances the veil of mystery surrounding how intricate and captivating structures emerge from simple random rulesets.
I invite you to search and reflect about the hidden layers of meaning, hoping you will find yours.

---

16 messages, 3 sampling methods, a small probability of receiving a broken signal.

â€¢ Clicking/tapping on the canvas shows a menu to pause, resume, reverse generation direction and download the current 1080x1080 pixels frame.

Done with p5.js

metadata.name: Round Round #80
metadata.description:
Primarily I focused on using circles as the main element in creating compositions. It involves arranging, manipulating and combining circles to form different shapes, patterns and designs.
Here, concepts such as symmetry, balance, rhythm and repetition are often examined. I used circles of different sizes, colors, textures, and opacity to create depth and visual interest, and added compositions like squiggly lines for complexity and variety.
The possibilities are endless when it comes to circles, as they have the freedom to experiment with different techniques and styles. It can take many forms including minimal, abstract designs, mandalas (spiritual symbols), optical illusions or even representational images made entirely of circles.
By focusing on the simplicity and versatility of circles, I have created a visual approach that evokes harmony, unity, and balance while also allowing for creative expression.

Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Pixel Management #838
metadata.description:
#tezpole has demonstrated to us all the importance of effective Cable Management. Intrigued by this challenge, I've delved deep into the pixels of this issue. ðŸ™‚

Drawing inspiration from Rev Dan Cattâ€™s 'Tally!' and applying similar principles of Cable Management, I've assembled a fun and free OE project.

This project dynamically evolves with each iteration.Grid is determined by a random value calculated as follows: the lower bound starts at 3 and increases incrementally with every 100 iterations, while the upper bound starts at 4 and increases with every 30 iterations. In practical terms, as the iteration count increases, both the minimum and maximum possible number of cols&rows gradually increase.

3200x3200px
Press [s] for .jpeg | Press [p] for .png
Made with p5.js

Rob Scalera | 2023

metadata.name: V0X3I\IA #144
metadata.description:
The wordÂ voxelÂ originated by analogy to "pixel", withÂ voÂ representing "volume" (instead of pixel's "picture") andÂ "el"Â representing "element";Â a similar formation withÂ elÂ for "element" is the word "texel".The termÂ hypervoxelÂ is a generalization of voxel forÂ higher-dimensional spaces.

In this collection, I focused on the smallest element of digital imaging, the pixel, and created movements through different animation scenarios. Random and repetitive animations are based on patterns that are erased and recreated each time. The movement, which pauses randomly in the flow and then erases and recreates every texture, culminates in a unique animation.

metadata.description:

metadata.name: The Visual Code #1
metadata.description:
The Visual Code is a collection of generative art that celebrates the jazzy, dynamic visuals inspired by Wassily Kandinsky, Jackson Pollock, Kazimir Malevich, Joan Miro and The Dave Brubeck Quartet's music.

Each piece uniquely expresses the artist's creativity and technical skill, showcasing the beauty and complexity of computer-generated visuals.

As a codegen artist, I am constantly in awe of the boundless potential of generative art. The ability to create unique, one-of-a-kind pieces using code is truly fascinating to me.

Generative art allows for a level of artistic expression that is simply not possible with traditional mediums. Using algorithms and mathematical principles allows for creating complex, dynamic visuals that are constantly evolving and changing.

What I find particularly interesting about generative art is its focus on the creation process. Rather than simply producing a static, finished product, the artist is more concerned with the journey and the process of creating the art. This allows for experimentation and exploration that is impossible in more traditional forms of art.

In my own work, I strive to push the boundaries of generative art and explore new possibilities. I constantly experiment with different algorithms and techniques to create something new and unique.

I am excited to continue learning and growing as an artist and to see where my passion for generative art will take me.

The collection is a tribute to the art of coding and its endless possibilities for artistic expression. From mesmerizing geometric patterns to pulsating colour fields, each piece in the collection is a testament to the endless potential of code as a medium for artistic creation.

Previous collectors are automatically on the reserve list for this exclusive collection. This is a rare opportunity to own a piece of generative art that captures the imagination and celebrates the beauty of code.

Press [S] to save.
